    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-08T23:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-08T23:35:00-05:00" n="600"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d600">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">391.1164/105: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-09T08:00:00+03:25"
                            >October 9, 1939—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:17 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>114. Shortly after the settlement of the school question last August a rumor
                    reached me from two different sources that the Government’s action against the
                    schools had been due to “Soviet intrigue”. I considered the rumor too fantastic
                    to merit serious thought but in the <pb facs="0540" n="534" xml:id="pg_534"/>
                    light of subsequent events described in my 103, September 18, 10 a.m. and 112,
                    October 3, 2 p.m.,<note n="4" xml:id="d600fn4">Neither printed.</note> I now
                    feel that it cannot be entirely disregarded. It is quite possible that Russia
                    which is not permitted to have any schools in Iran informed the Iranian
                    Government that it would insist on the same rights as other nations. And the
                    Iranian Government rather than risk resumption of poisonous propaganda which has
                    always emanated from Soviet schools, but unable to afford to annoy Moscow, then
                    promised to eliminate also the remaining foreign educational institutions.</p>
                <p>Although Iranians are always apt to take shortsighted view of events, they
                    probably realized in this instance that they were on the eve of a renewal of
                    Russian efforts to win Iran—like China—to communism and therefore wanted to
                    prolong breathing space in the hope that the Soviets were only play-acting to
                    frighten the democracies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
